Explanation:

I examined the controller method App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\UserController@update and related classes to determine possible responses for PATCH /v1/users/{user}.

Key points found:
- The update action receives a UsersRequest which enforces validation rules (name required string with AlphaName rule, email required unique email). When validation fails Laravel returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity with a JSON body containing "message" and "errors".
- The controller calls $this->authorize('update', $user). If the authenticated user is not authorized, Laravel will return a 403 Forbidden (authorization failure) with a JSON "message" by default. If the user is not authenticated at all, middleware/exception handling produces a 401 Unauthenticated response with a JSON "message".
- If the {user} route-model binding fails (no such user), Laravel returns a 404 Not Found with a JSON "message".
- On success the controller returns a UserResource which serializes the user into a JSON object containing the fields defined in app/Http/Resources/User.php:
  - id (integer)
  - name (string)
  - email (string, email)
  - provider (string|null)
  - provider_id (string|null)
  - registered_at (string, ISO-8601 date-time)
  - comments_count (integer)
  - posts_count (integer)
  - roles (array of role objects with id (integer) and name (string))
- I used common Laravel response shapes for error cases: a JSON object with "message" (string) for 401, 403, 404, and for 422 I included "message" plus an "errors" object whose properties are arrays of strings (typical Laravel validation error format).

